Example of adiabatic compression.
The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression. The simplifying assumptions are: the uncompressed volume of the cylinder is 1000 cm (one litre); the gas within is nearly pure nitrogen (thus a diatomic gas with five degrees of freedom and so formula_13 = 7/5); the compression ratio of the engine is 10:1 (that is, the 1000 cm volume of uncompressed gas be reduced to 100 cm by the piston); and that the uncompressed gas is at approximately room temperature and pressure (a warm room temperature of ~27 °C or 300 K, and a pressure of 1 bar ~ 100 kPa, or about 14.7 PSI, i.e. typical sea-level atmospheric pressure).
